---
import ContentLayout from '../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import Card from '../components/Card.astro';
import Button from '../components/Button.astro';
import Alert from '../components/Alert.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
	title="Resources for Parents"
	description="Comprehensive internet safety guidance for parents to protect their children online with age-appropriate filters and family strategies."
>
	<Fragment slot="breadcrumb">
		<ol>
			<li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
			<li>Parents</li>
		</ol>
	</Fragment>

	<Alert type="info">
		<strong>New to internet safety?</strong> Start with our <a href="/guides/age-appropriate-internet">Age-Appropriate Internet Guide</a> for a step-by-step introduction.
	</Alert>

	<section>
		<h2>Why Internet Safety Matters for Families</h2>
		<p>
			In today's digital world, children have unprecedented access to information and communication.
			While technology offers incredible learning opportunities, it also presents risks that parents
			need to understand and address.
		</p>
		<p>
			Effective internet safety isn't just about blocking content — it's about creating a healthy
			digital environment that combines technical protections with open communication, education,
			and age-appropriate boundaries.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>Getting Started: Your First Steps</h2>
		<p>
			Protecting your family online can feel overwhelming, but you don't have to do everything at once.
			Start with these foundational steps:
		</p>
		<ol>
			<li>
				<strong>Assess your current situation:</strong> Make a list of all devices your children use —
				phones, tablets, computers, gaming consoles, smart TVs.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Choose your protection strategy:</strong> Decide between network-level filtering (protects all devices),
				device-level controls (protects specific devices), or a combination of both.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Start with the easiest wins:</strong> Enable built-in parental controls on devices and set up
				basic DNS filtering on your home network.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Have age-appropriate conversations:</strong> Talk with your children about why these protections
				exist and what healthy internet use looks like.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Review and adjust regularly:</strong> As your children grow and technology changes, revisit
				your approach every few months.
			</li>
		</ol>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>Protection by Age Group</h2>
		<p>
			Different ages require different approaches. Here's a general framework:
		</p>

		<div class="age-groups">
			<div class="age-group">
				<h3>Young Children (Ages 5-8)</h3>
				<ul>
					<li>Heavily restricted, curated content only</li>
					<li>Direct supervision during all screen time</li>
					<li>Kid-specific apps and platforms (YouTube Kids, PBS Kids)</li>
					<li>No social media or messaging</li>
					<li>Time limits: 1-2 hours per day maximum</li>
				</ul>
			</div>

			<div class="age-group">
				<h3>Preteens (Ages 9-12)</h3>
				<ul>
					<li>Filtered content with some educational freedom</li>
					<li>Supervised social media (if any) with parental oversight</li>
					<li>Check-ins before and after screen time</li>
					<li>Gaming with age-appropriate ratings</li>
					<li>Time limits: 2-3 hours per day with breaks</li>
				</ul>
			</div>

			<div class="age-group">
				<h3>Teenagers (Ages 13-17)</h3>
				<ul>
					<li>Filtered content with increased autonomy</li>
					<li>Social media with clear expectations and boundaries</li>
					<li>Open conversations about online risks and experiences</li>
					<li>Accountability rather than just restriction</li>
					<li>Flexible time limits based on responsibility</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>Types of Protection</h2>
		<p>
			Modern internet safety requires a layered approach. Here are the main categories of protection:
		</p>

		<div class="protection-cards">
			<Card
				title="Network-Level Protection"
				description="DNS filtering and router settings that protect all devices connected to your home WiFi."
				href="/methods#network"
			/>
			<Card
				title="Device Controls"
				description="Built-in parental controls on phones, tablets, computers, and gaming consoles."
				href="/methods#devices"
			/>
			<Card
				title="Software Solutions"
				description="Third-party filtering software and monitoring applications for additional protection."
				href="/methods#software"
			/>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>Common Challenges and Solutions</h2>

		<h3>Challenge: Kids bypassing filters</h3>
		<p>
			<strong>Solution:</strong> Use multiple layers of protection (network + device + app level).
			Combine technical controls with conversations about why protections exist. Make bypassing
			filters a serious family rule with clear consequences.
		</p>

		<h3>Challenge: Age-appropriate content varies by child</h3>
		<p>
			<strong>Solution:</strong> Create separate user profiles or accounts for each child with
			age-appropriate settings. Many platforms (Windows, iOS, Android) support multiple child accounts
			with different restriction levels.
		</p>

		<h3>Challenge: Balancing protection with trust</h3>
		<p>
			<strong>Solution:</strong> As children mature, gradually shift from restriction to accountability.
			Use monitoring and accountability software that creates transparency rather than just blocking.
			Have regular conversations about their online experiences.
		</p>

		<h3>Challenge: Different devices need different approaches</h3>
		<p>
			<strong>Solution:</strong> Start with network-level DNS filtering for baseline protection across
			all devices. Then add device-specific controls for phones and tablets that leave the house.
		</p>

		<h3>Challenge: Keeping up with new apps and platforms</h3>
		<p>
			<strong>Solution:</strong> Establish a family rule that new apps must be approved before installation.
			Use device management features to control app downloads. Stay informed through resources like
			Common Sense Media.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>Recommended Solutions for Parents</h2>
		<p>
			Based on ease of use, effectiveness, and family-friendliness, here are our top recommendations:
		</p>

		<h3>Best for Beginners</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>DNS Filtering:</strong> CleanBrowsing or OpenDNS Family Shield (free, easy setup)</li>
			<li><strong>iPhone/iPad:</strong> Built-in Screen Time controls</li>
			<li><strong>Android:</strong> Google Family Link</li>
			<li><strong>Windows:</strong> Microsoft Family Safety</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Best Comprehensive Solution</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Network + Devices:</strong> Circle Home Plus or Bark</li>
			<li>Provides filtering, time limits, and monitoring across all devices</li>
			<li>Monthly subscription required but covers the whole family</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Best for Maximum Protection</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>Combine DNS filtering (network level) + built-in device controls + monitoring software</li>
			<li>Creates multiple layers that work together</li>
			<li>More complex to set up but most effective</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="cta-box">
			<h4>Ready to implement protection?</h4>
			<p>Browse our step-by-step guides for your specific devices and needs.</p>
			<Button href="/methods" size="lg">View All Protection Methods</Button>
		</div>
	</section>

	<Fragment slot="sidebar">
		<div class="sidebar-section">
			<h3>Quick Links</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><a href="#getting-started">Getting Started</a></li>
				<li><a href="#age-groups">Protection by Age</a></li>
				<li><a href="#types">Types of Protection</a></li>
				<li><a href="#challenges">Common Challenges</a></li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<div class="sidebar-section">
			<h3>Popular Guides</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><a href="/guides/dns-filtering">Setting Up DNS Filtering</a></li>
				<li><a href="/guides/ios-screen-time">iPhone Screen Time Setup</a></li>
				<li><a href="/guides/android-family-link">Android Family Link</a></li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<div class="sidebar-section">
			<h3>Need Help?</h3>
			<p>
				Can't find what you're looking for? Check our <a href="/faq">FAQ</a> or
				<a href="/contact">contact us</a> for personalized guidance.
			</p>
		</div>
	</Fragment>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
	section {
		margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
	}

	section h2 {
		margin-top: var(--space-8);
		margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
	}

	section h3 {
		margin-top: var(--space-6);
		margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
		color: var(--color-primary-600);
	}

	section p {
		margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
		line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
	}

	section ol,
	section ul {
		margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
	}

	section li {
		margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
		line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
	}

	.age-groups {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: 1fr;
		gap: var(--space-6);
		margin: var(--space-6) 0;
	}

	@media (min-width: 768px) {
		.age-groups {
			grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
		}
	}

	.age-group {
		background-color: var(--color-gray-50);
		padding: var(--space-6);
		border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
		border: 1px solid var(--color-gray-200);
	}

	.age-group h3 {
		color: var(--color-primary-600);
		font-size: var(--text-lg);
		margin-top: 0;
		margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
	}

	.age-group ul {
		margin-bottom: 0;
		padding-left: var(--space-5);
	}

	.age-group li {
		font-size: var(--text-sm);
		margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
	}

	.protection-cards {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: 1fr;
		gap: var(--space-6);
		margin: var(--space-6) 0;
	}

	@media (min-width: 768px) {
		.protection-cards {
			grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
		}
	}

	.cta-box {
		background: linear-gradient(
			135deg,
			var(--color-primary-50) 0%,
			var(--color-secondary-50) 100%
		);
		padding: var(--space-8);
		border-radius: var(--radius-xl);
		text-align: center;
		margin-top: var(--space-8);
	}

	.cta-box h4 {
		font-size: var(--text-2xl);
		margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
	}

	.cta-box p {
		font-size: var(--text-lg);
		margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
		color: var(--color-gray-700);
	}
</style>
